Context¶

Diabetes is one of the most frequent diseases worldwide and the number of diabetic patients are growing over the years. The main cause of diabetes remains unknown, yet scientists believe that both genetic factors and environmental lifestyle play a major role in diabetes.

A few years ago research was done on a tribe in America called the Akimel O'odham tribe or "River People" (also know as the Pima tribe). In this tribe, it was found that the ladies are prone to diabetes very early. Several constraints were placed on the selection of these instances from a larger database. In particular, all patients were females at least 21 years old of Pima Indian heritage.

Objective¶

Here, we analyze different aspects of Diabetes in the Akimel O'odham tribe through Exploratory Data Analysis.

Data Dictionary¶

The dataset has the following information:

  • Pregnancies: Number of times pregnant (count)
  • Glucose: Plasma glucose concentration over 2 hours in an oral glucose tolerance test $\text{ *missing units }$ $\left( \frac{mg}{dL} \right)$ are the conventional units
  • BloodPressure: Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg)
  • SkinThickness: Triceps skin fold thickness (mm)
  • Insulin: 2-Hour serum insulin (mu U/ml) $\implies$ $\left(\frac{\mu IU}{ml}\right)$ are the conventional insulin concetration units
  • BMI: Body mass index (weight in kg/(height in m)^2) $\implies$$\left( \frac{kg}{m^2} \right)$
  • DiabetesPedigreeFunction: A function that scores the likelihood of diabetes based on family history. (scalar)
  • Age: Age in years
  • Outcome: Class variable (0: a person is not diabetic or 1: a person is diabetic)

*Note missing units, let's try not to harm anyone with careless mitakes.

Write your Answer here:¶

Ans 9: For our explaination we'll select 'Age' as it is the most interpretable varible. The 'count' tells us the number of data points in the sample. The 'mean' shown here is the Aritmetic average and measures the central dendancy of the age. The 'std' or standard deviation is a measure of the amount of variation in age. The 'max' and 'min' provide the range of age values. The '25%', '50%' and '75%' measures represent the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd quartiles respectively. These quartiles divide the number of data points into four parts roughly four equal parts, where 50% of the data is above and below the 2nd quartile, 75% of the data points are above the 1st and similarly 75% of the data points are below the 3rd quartile.

See also: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quartile¶

Q 10. Plot the distribution plot for the variable 'BloodPressure'. Write detailed observations from the plot. (2 Marks)¶

In [12]:
sns.displot(pima['BloodPressure'], kind = 'kde')
plt.grid() # grids improve readablity
plt.show()

Write your Answer here:¶

Ans 10: This visulizaton of the distribution of 'BloodPressure' measurements shows a single modal central tendancy. The kernel density estimate (KDE) opition improves the interpretablity of this graph by smoothing random noise in the data. This smoothing helps us to see most measurements fall between 45 and 100 (mm Hg) with most frequent measurement of around 72 (mm Hg).

KDE plot with smoothing bandwidth adjusted¶

Take care, an over-smoothed estimate might erase meaningful features while under-smoothing can obscure the shape of the distibution.

In [13]:
sns.displot( pima['BloodPressure'], kind = 'kde', bw_adjust=.95)
plt.grid() # grids improve readablity
sns.displot( pima['BloodPressure'], kind = 'kde', bw_adjust=.25)
plt.grid() # grids improve readablity

Ans 19: The Interquartile Ranges are as follows: Pregnancies 5.0000 Glucose 40.5000 BloodPressure 16.0000 SkinThickness 12.0000 Insulin 48.2500 BMI 9.1000 DiabetesPedigreeFunction 0.3825 Age 17.0000 Outcome 1.0000 Quartiles divide the number of data points into four parts roughly four equal parts, where 50% of the data is above and below the 2nd quartile, 75% of the data points are above the 1st and similarly 75% of the data points are below the 3rd quartile. The IQR contains the median value and 50% of all the samples, the central values of the sample. The IQR provides a measure for determining the standard deviation of the sample. The boxplot is used to visualize the IQR, meadian value, standard devation and outliers. Below we show a boxplot for each column of data and find that it not appropriate for catagorical data.
